<HEADLINE>
<P>
THEATER REVIEW; FISHBURNE'S 'RIFF RAFF' A GRITTY EVOLUTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT COLLINS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 "Riff Raff," the new play written and directed by film actor Laurence 
Fishburne, has the high energy and tight focus of a '90s film noir. The 
creators call it a work in progress, but with its edgy acting and superior 
production values this gritty one-act at Theatre Geo hardly needs a disclaimer. 
</P>
<P>
 The setting is a trashed and abandoned flat on New York's Lower East Side, 
where ex-con Mike (Fishburne) and junkie Torch (Titus Welliver) have fled after 
botching a heroin heist. There they run into Tony (rapper Heavy D), Mike's old 
partner in crime, who may or may not be working for the drug kingpin Mike and 
Torch just robbed. 
</P>
<P>
 Over a tense 24-hour period, with car alarms and police sirens blaring outside 
the hide-out, the trio smoke, eat, reminisce and shoot the breeze as a series 
of betrayals and revelations alters the geometry among the characters. By the 
time the script ratchets down, Fishburne has shown how these urban desperadoes 
are forced to accept their grim destiny. 
</P>
<P>
 As a writer, Fishburne seems inspired by David Mamet's "American Buffalo." 
"Riff Raff" never matches Mamet's deft, economical use of language, and some 
plot points seem contrived and half-baked. 
</P>
<P>
 But director Fishburne keeps the pace brisk and suspenseful, and all three 
actors turn in crisp, tough portrayals. 
</P>
<P>
 * "Riff Raff," Theatre Geo, 1229 N. Highland Ave., Hollywood. 
Thursdays-Saturdays, 8 p.m.; Sundays, 1 p.m. Dark Thanksgiving. Ends Dec. 18. 
$20. (213) 466-1767. Running time: 1 hour, 25 minutes. SCOTT COLLINS 
</P>
</TEXT>
