 Initially, police had been unable to identify the body and held onto the thumb 
in hopes it would eventually yield clues. A state crime lab injected some 
chemicals to raise the ridges on the thumb, and Solano's prints were found on 
file at the Immigration and Naturalization Service. 
</P>
<P>
 "Back in '76, they didn't have a lot of technology we have now," sheriff's 
Detective Jay Glover said. 
