<HEADLINE>
<P>
FATHER, 23, KILLED BY ROBBER WHILE WIFE FLEES WITH BABY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NICHOLAS RICCARDI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The robber grabbed Jose Torres Jr. by the neck and began dragging him away 
from his car while he held his 4-month-old son, police said. Torres' wife 
leaped from the passenger side of the car and grabbed the baby, as Torres told 
her to run into their apartment building and call the police. 
</P>
<P>
 The sound of gunshots that police said killed her 23-year-old husband echoed 
through the apartment unit from where she was calling for help. 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles police detectives said Torres died Tuesday after spending the 
night in Northridge Hospital Medical Center's intensive care unit. Police were 
searching for the man who shot him in the head and shoulder Monday night after 
Torres refused to give up his money. 
</P>
<P>
 Torres had driven his family into the parking lot of their Panorama City 
apartment building about 8:30 p.m. As he left the car, he was grabbed by the 
robber, LAPD Sgt. Joseph Brazas said. Torres told the robber he was carrying a 
baby, and managed to hand the child to his wife, who fled inside the 
three-story building, Brazas said. 
</P>
<P>
 The robber took Torres' wallet, which contained no money, Brazas said. They 
then began to struggle, and the robber shot Torres twice, in the head and 
shoulder, with a semiautomatic pistol. 
</P>
<P>
 Torres' wife, meanwhile, ran into the building and pounded on the doors of 
several units. Two boys, Steve Bustillos, 15, and Ricky Hardiman, 12, answered 
her pleas. As she used their phone, the youths said, they heard the gunshots 
and ran out with another friend. 
</P>
<P>
 When they arrived at the parking lot they saw the robber flee. Bustillos said 
the robber ducked through a tear in the chain fence by the gated lot and ran to 
the street. The boys then ran to Torres.  
</P>
<P>
 Bustillos said that while cars in the lot are occasionally broken into or 
vandalized, this is the first violence at the building. 
</P>
<P>
 "Everybody in this building tries to keep things up," chasing off taggers and 
vandals, Bustillos said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
