<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: SUPERVISORS-ELECT TO ATTEND CEO TALKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARLOS LOZANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ventura County's two newly elected supervisors will be included in board 
discussions on replacing outgoing chief administrator Richard Wittenberg, 
officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 After meeting in closed session, the Board of Supervisors agreed Tuesday to 
invite Judy Mikels and Frank Schillo, who will be sworn in Jan. 3, to future 
meetings regarding the selection of a new county manager. 
</P>
<P>
 Schillo said it is important that the two incoming supervisors participate in 
the search for Wittenberg's successor. 
</P>
<P>
 He said that he had talked earlier to Supervisors Vicky Howard and John Flynn 
about being included in the board's discussions, but that it had not been made 
clear until Tuesday whether that was legally possible. 
</P>
<P>
 Supervisor Maggie Kildee said the board plans to meet in closed session next 
Tuesday to discuss naming an interim manager as well as finding a permanent 
replacement. 
</P>
<P>
 Wittenberg, the county's top executive for 16 years, surprised officials last 
week by announcing that he will step down Jan. 23 to take a job in Santa Clara 
County. He said he accepted the new job because he wanted the challenge of 
working in a more urban county. CARLOS LOZANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
